Modern frontend applications are highly interactive and real-time. They respond to user actions, server pushes, WebSocket messages, feature flags, and even events from other micro-frontends. Managing this complexity with direct component communication quickly leads to tight coupling, spaghetti code, and fragile systems.
Event-Driven Architecture (EDA) addresses this by treating events as the primary way components, services, and modules communicate. Instead of direct calls, producers emit events, and consumers react to them — promoting loose coupling and high scalability.
Angular is exceptionally well-suited for EDA thanks to its reactive foundation: RxJS, Signals, and NgRx.

Why Angular Excels at Event-Driven Architecture
Angular was built with reactivity in mind:

• RxJS — Powerful streams for complex event pipelines

• Signals (Angular 17+) — Fine-grained, lightweight reactivity

• NgRx — Formalizes events as Actions with predictable flows

• Dependency Injection — Makes custom Event Buses and services easy to provide and mock

• Module Federation — Enables events to flow between independently deployed micro-frontends
This rich toolkit allows you to implement everything from simple component communication to enterprise-scale event systems.

Recommended Structure for Event-Driven Code
