Core Patterns in Event-Driven Angular
1. RxJS for Event Pipelines (The Foundation)
RxJS is the backbone of event-driven flows in Angular.
Real-World Example: Product Catalog + Cart Synchronization
// core/events/product.events.ts
export const PRODUCT_EVENTS = {
PRODUCT_SELECTED: 'PRODUCT_SELECTED',
STOCK_UPDATED: 'STOCK_UPDATED',
PRODUCT_ADDED_TO_CART: 'PRODUCT_ADDED_TO_CART'
} as const;
// core/event-bus.service.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class EventBusService {
private eventBus$ = new Subject<AppEvent>(); emit<T = any>(type: string, payload?: T) {
this.eventBus$.next({ type, payload, timestamp: Date.now() });
}
on<T = any>(eventType: string): Observable<T> {
return this.eventBus$.pipe(
filter(event => event.type === eventType),
map(event => event.payload as T),
distinctUntilChanged()
);
}
}
interface AppEvent {
type: string;
payload?: any;
timestamp: number;
}
Listening and Reacting Across Features:
// presentation/components/product-card.component.ts
export class ProductCardComponent {
constructor(private eventBus: EventBusService) {}onAddToCart(product: Product) {
this.eventBus.emit(PRODUCT_EVENTS.PRODUCT_ADDED_TO_CART, {
productId: product.id,
quantity: 1
});
}
}
// presentation/components/cart-icon.component.ts (in a completely different module)
export class CartIconComponent implements OnInit {
itemCount$ = this.eventBus.on<CartUpdate>(PRODUCT_EVENTS.PRODUCT_ADDED_TO_CART).pipe(
scan((count, update) => count + update.quantity, 0)
);
constructor(private eventBus: EventBusService) {}
}
This achieves true loose coupling — the Product Card doesn’t know the Cart exists.

2. Signals for Local & Component-Level Reactivity (Angular 17+)
Signals are excellent for fine-grained, synchronous reactivity:
TypeScript
// presentation/pages/product-detail.component.ts
export class ProductDetailComponent {
private readonly eventBus = inject(EventBusService); // Local state
selectedVariant = signal<ProductVariant | null>(null);
quantity = signal(1)
// Computed values
totalPrice = computed(() => {
const variant = this.selectedVariant();
return variant ? variant.price * this.quantity() : 0;
});
constructor() {
// React to global events
this.eventBus.on<StockUpdate>(PRODUCT_EVENTS.STOCK_UPDATED).subscribe(update => {
if (update.productId === this.product().id) {
// Update local signal
this.updateStockAvailability(update.newStock);
}
});
}
}

3. NgRx + Event-Driven Flows
NgRx can both consume and emit events, making it a powerful participant in EDA.
// presentation/state/cart/cart.effects.ts
@Injectable()
export class CartEffects {
// Listen to external events
syncCartWithProductUpdates$ = createEffect(() =>
this.eventBus.on<ProductStockUpdate>(PRODUCT_EVENTS.STOCK_UPDATED).pipe(
map(update => updateCartItemStock({ productId: update.productId, newStock: update.newStock }))
)
);
// Broadcast cart changes to the rest of the app
broadcastCartUpdates$ = createEffect(() =>
this.actions$.pipe(
ofType(addToCartSuccess),
tap(({ cart }) => {
this.eventBus.emit(PRODUCT_EVENTS.PRODUCT_ADDED_TO_CART, {
productId: cart.lastAddedProductId,
quantity: cart.lastAddedQuantity
});
})
), { dispatch: false }
);
constructor(
private actions$: Actions,
private eventBus: EventBusService
) {}
}
Real-World Scenario: Enterprise E-commerce Platform
Imagine a large e-commerce application with multiple teams:

• Product Team emits PRODUCT_PRICE_CHANGED

• Cart Team listens and updates totals

• Wishlist Team reacts to price drops

• Analytics Team tracks all events

• Micro-frontend (Admin Panel) listens for ORDER_PLACED events
All teams work independently without tight dependencies. This is the power of Event-Driven Architecture.

Benefits & Trade-offs
Benefits:

• Excellent loose coupling between features

• Easy to add new listeners without changing producers

• Natural fit for real-time applications

• Great for micro-frontends communication

• Improved testability (mock events easily)
Challenges:

• Can lead to “event soup” if overused (too many event types)

• Debugging distributed events can be harder

• Need good naming conventions and documentation for events
Tip: Start with a typed Event Bus and central event definitions.

Conclusion
Event-Driven Architecture transforms your Angular application into a reactive, flexible, and scalable system. By combining RxJS for complex flows, Signals for local reactivity, NgRx for state, and a well-designed Event Bus, you can build frontends that handle complexity gracefully.
This pattern pairs beautifully with Clean Architecture and CQRS, forming a solid foundation for enterprise applications.
